MARCHING orders are coming for deputy national directors of public prosecution Nomgcobo Jiba and Lawrence Mrwebi.The pair have been requested to give reasons why they should not be suspended.The Presidency yesterday issued a statement about giving notice to suspend the two advocates, pending an inquiry into their fitness to hold office.Last month, Jiba and Mrwebi made headlines after the news that both had been struck off the roll of advocates.The case involves their decision to drop charges against suspended police crime intelligence head Richard Mdluli.It also includes the &ldquo;spy tapes&rdquo; matter relating to the dropping of corruption charges against President Jacob Zuma and the case of suspended KZN Hawks head Johan Booysen into the alleged Cato Manor &ldquo;death squad&rdquo;.The president&rsquo;s decision follows the recent judgment of the North Gauteng High Court in the matter of the General Council of the Bar of South Africa vs Jiba, Mrwebi and Sibongile Mzinyathi, in which the court ordered that the names of the two advocates be removed from the roll. The president requested the two advocates to give reasons why they should not be suspended.&ldquo;After hearing the two advocates, the president will then take a decision on whether or not to suspend them,&rdquo; the statement read.